\begin{frame}{Example: Calculating Probabilities with Normal
Distributions}
\phantomsection\label{example-calculating-probabilities-with-normal-distributions}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  The average male height is \textasciitilde70'' (5'10'') and
  approximately follows the distribution \(N(70, 3)\).
\item
  The average female height is \textasciitilde63'' (5'3'') and
  approximately follows the distribution \(N(63, 3)\).
\item
  What is the probability that a random male is taller than the average
  female but still shorter than the average male?
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{What's the sample space?}
\phantomsection\label{whats-the-sample-space}
\includegraphics{class14_files/figure-beamer/unnamed-chunk-2-1.pdf}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Visualizing the problem}
\phantomsection\label{visualizing-the-problem}
\includegraphics{class14_files/figure-beamer/unnamed-chunk-3-1.pdf}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Breaking it down\ldots{}}
\phantomsection\label{breaking-it-down}
\begin{figure}[H]

{\centering \includegraphics{class14_files/mediabag/probability-differen.png-raw=true}

}

\caption{You can think of this problem as the difference between two
percentiles.}

\end{figure}%
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Calculating the difference in R}
\phantomsection\label{calculating-the-difference-in-r}
The probability that a man is below average in height for men but above
average in height for women is the difference between the percentile for
70'' and the percentile for 63'' in the distribution of male heights or
49\%.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{70}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{mean =} \DecValTok{70}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{sd =} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FunctionTok{pnorm}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{63}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{mean =} \DecValTok{70}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{sd =} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{frame}{Random Sampling}
\phantomsection\label{random-sampling}
Why do we sample?

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Easier, cheaper, convenience, etc.
\item
  Hard to do a census
\end{itemize}

What are the downsides of sampling?

\begin{itemize}
\item
  May not represent study/target population
\item
  Methods might introduce bias
\item
  Results could be due to chance
\end{itemize}

How certain are we that our data is representative?
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example: Estimating Proportions}
\phantomsection\label{example-estimating-proportions}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  Bureau of Justice Statistics September 2021 Special Report on
  Recidivism of Prisoners
\item
  Sampled 73,600 prisoner records from National Corrections Reporting
  Program on 409,300 state prisoners released across 24 states in 2008,
  representing 69\% of all persons released from state prisons
\item
  89\% of sampled prisoners were male, and 11\% of sampled prisoners
  were female.
\item
  42.9\% of sampled prisoners were rearrested within 1 year. 43.9\% of
  male sampled prisoners were rearrested within 1 year. 34.4\% of female
  sampled prisoners were rearrested within 1 year.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example: Independence}
\phantomsection\label{example-independence}
Is a prisoner being rearrested within 1 year of their release
independent of their sex?

\emph{Remember: when 2 events are independent,
\(P(B) \approx P(B|A) \approx P(B|A')\)}

\[
\begin{aligned}
P(\operatorname{rearrested and male}) &= P(\operatorname{male}) \times P(\operatorname{rearrested}|\operatorname{male}) \\
&\approx P(\operatorname{male}) \times P(\operatorname{rearrested})
\end{aligned}
\]
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Point Estimation}
\phantomsection\label{point-estimation}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  We are interested in population-level parameters
\item
  Complete populations are difficult (or impossible) to collect data
  from
\item
  The \textbf{\emph{sample statistic}} can be used as a
  \textbf{\emph{point estimate}} for a population parameter in
  sufficiently large samples
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Population Parameters versus Sample Statistics}
\phantomsection\label{population-parameters-versus-sample-statistics}
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Measure & Parameter & Statistic \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
Mean & \(\mu\) & \(\bar{x}\) \\
Proportion & \(p\) & \(\hat{p}\) \\
Difference in Means & \(\mu_1-\mu_2\) & \(\bar{x}_1-\bar{x}_2\) \\
Difference in Proportions & \(p_1-p_2\) & \(\hat{p}_1-\hat{p}_2\) \\
Standard Deviation & \(\sigma\) & \(s\) \\
Correlation & \(\rho\) & \(r\) \\
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\end{longtable}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Sampling Distribution}
\phantomsection\label{sampling-distribution}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  A \textbf{\emph{sampling distribution}} is a distribution of sample
  statistics for different samples of the same size from the same
  population
\item
  Not actually observed in the real world, a ``hypothetical'' population
  distribution
\item
  Sampling distributions also have location and scales
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Uncertainty \& Sampling Error}
\phantomsection\label{uncertainty-sampling-error}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  What are sources of error we COULD know?
\item
  What are sources of error we CAN'T know?
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Central Limit Theorem}
\phantomsection\label{central-limit-theorem}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  A distribution of sample means approximates a normal distribution as
  the sample size gets larger
\item
  Requires \textbf{\emph{independent, identically distributed (I.I.D)}}
  variables

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    Each observation is \emph{independent} of the next
  \item
    Each observation comes from the same source distribution
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Sample size must be sufficient for estimates to be valid
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Standard Error of the Sample Statistic}
\phantomsection\label{standard-error-of-the-sample-statistic}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{\emph{Standard error (SE)}} is the \emph{standard deviation}
  of the sample statistic
\item
  Describes the scale (i.e.~variability, sampling error) of the sampling
  distribution
\item
  For a distribution of sample means, \(SE=\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\)
\item
  For a distribution of sample proportions,
  \(SE=\sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}\)
\end{itemize}

As \(n\) increases, the standard error \(SE\) decreases.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{What do sample means have to do with proportions?}
\phantomsection\label{what-do-sample-means-have-to-do-with-proportions}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  For a binary category, if you coded the 2 classes as \(0\) and \(1\),
  the sample mean \(\bar{x}\) equals the sample proportion \(\hat{p}\)
  of \(1\)'s.
\item
  Example: You flip a coin 5 times, and it's tails 3 times.
\end{itemize}

\begin{columns}[T]
\begin{column}{0.48\textwidth}
\[
\begin{aligned}
\hat{p}&= \frac{\operatorname{count}(\operatorname{tails})}{\operatorname{count}(\operatorname{flips})} \\
&= \frac{3}{5} 
\end{aligned}
\]
\end{column}

\begin{column}{0.48\textwidth}
\[
\begin{aligned}
\bar{x}&=\frac{\operatorname{sum}(0, 0, 1, 1, 1)}{n} \\
&=\frac{3}{5}
\end{aligned}
\]
\end{column}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Central Limit Theorem for Sample Proportions}
\phantomsection\label{central-limit-theorem-for-sample-proportions}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\emph{Assumption}}: Sample proportions will be nearly normally
  distributed with mean \(p\) and standard deviation
  \(\sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}\) (i.e.~standard error)
\end{itemize}

\[
\hat{p} \sim N\left(p, \sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}\right)
\]
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Requirements for CLT for Proportions}
\phantomsection\label{requirements-for-clt-for-proportions}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  Need a sufficiently large sample size!

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    \(np > 10\)
  \item
    \(n(1-p) > 10\)
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Need \textbf{\emph{i.i.d.}} samples
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Central Limit Theorem for Sample Means}
\phantomsection\label{central-limit-theorem-for-sample-means}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\emph{Assumption}}: Sample means will be nearly normally
  distributed with mean \(\mu\) and standard deviation
  \(\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\) (standard error)
\end{itemize}

\[
\bar{x} \sim N\left(\mu, \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)
\]
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Requirements for CLT for Means}
\phantomsection\label{requirements-for-clt-for-means}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  Need a sufficiently large sample size!

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    \(n>30\) when underlying distribution is normal
  \item
    Need larger \(n\) when underlying distribution is skewed
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Need \textbf{\emph{i.i.d.}} samples
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Statistical Inference and Hypothesis Testing}
\phantomsection\label{statistical-inference-and-hypothesis-testing}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  We use sample statistics to describe study populations and estimate
  parameters using sampling distributions
\item
  We also describe the variability of our measure and quantify our
  uncertainty regarding our estimate
\item
  We use the overlap between theoretical distributions to decide how
  meaningful the differences between groups are
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example: COVID-19 Vaccination \& Myocarditis}
\phantomsection\label{example-covid-19-vaccination-myocarditis}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  Study in Denmark of 4,931,775 individuals ages 12+ or older from
  2020-10-01 to 2021-10-05
\item
  3,482,295 individuals in the study were vaccinated and 269 developed
  myocarditis. 48 individuals were vaccinated \emph{and} developed
  myocarditis.
\item
  Does the probability of developing myocarditis vary by whether or not
  someone has been vaccinated against COVID-19?
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example: Estimating the Population Probability of
Myocarditis}
\phantomsection\label{example-estimating-the-population-probability-of-myocarditis}
If 269 of the 4,931,775 individuals sampled regardless of vaccination
status, what is our \textbf{\emph{point estimate}} (i.e.~sample
statistic) for the probability of developing myocarditis in our study
population?

\[
\begin{aligned}
  \hat{p}&=\frac{\operatorname{count}(\operatorname{cases})}{\operatorname{count}(\operatorname{subjects})} \\
  &= \frac{269}{4,931,775} \\
  &= 0.00005
\end{aligned}
\]
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example: Standard Error of the Measurement}
\phantomsection\label{example-standard-error-of-the-measurement}
If 269 of the 4,931,775 individuals sampled regardless of vaccination
status, what is the \textbf{\emph{standard error}} of our sample
statistic \(\hat{p}=0.00005\), the probability of developing myocarditis
in our study population?

\[
\begin{aligned}
  SE_\hat{p} &= \sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}} \\
  &= \sqrt{\frac{0.00005(1-0.00005)}{4,931,775}} \\
  &= 0.000003
\end{aligned}
\]
\end{frame}

\phantomsection\label{example-myocarditis-all-sampling-distribution}
The proportion of all individuals in the study population who develop
myocarditis has a sampling distribution of \(N(0.00005, 0.000003)\).

\begin{frame}{Example: 68-95-99.7 Rule}
\phantomsection\label{example-68-95-99.7-rule}
If my population has the theoretical sampling distribution
\(p \sim N(0.00005, 0.000003)\)\ldots{}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  What is the proportion of theoretical samples with a sample proportion
  \(0.000047 \le \hat{p} \le 0.000053\)?
\item
  What is the proportion of theoretical samples with a sample proportion
  \(0.000041 \le \hat{p} \le 0.000059\)?
\item
  In what range do 95\% of the theoretical sample means occur?
\end{itemize}

95\% Confidence Interval = \((0.000044, 0.000056)\)
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example: Probability of Myocarditis in Vaccinated}
\phantomsection\label{example-probability-of-myocarditis-in-vaccinated}
If 48 of the 3,482,295 vaccinated individuals developed myocarditis,
what is our \textbf{\emph{point estimate}} (i.e.~sample statistic) for
the probability of developing myocarditis in our vaccinated population?

\[
\begin{aligned}
  \hat{p}&=\frac{\operatorname{count}(\operatorname{vaccinated cases})}{\operatorname{count}(\operatorname{vaccinated subjects})} \\
  &= \frac{48}{3,482,295} \\
  &= 0.00001
\end{aligned}
\]
\end{frame}
